x’s judicious investigation of official correspondence, treaties, newspapers and magazines, diaries, and maps reveals a locally developed system of accommodation that promoted peaceful interactions but enabled violent reprisals when agreements were broken. This outstanding contribution to scholarship on early North America questions the nature and practice of imperial expansion in the face of Indigenous territorial strength.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIndians of North AmericaxLand tenurexHistoryy17th centuryxAtlantic Provinces. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLand tenurexHistoryy18th centuryxAtlantic Provinces. 0aLand settlementxHistoryy17th centuryxAtlantic Provinces. 0aLand settlementxHistoryy18th centuryxAtlantic Provinces. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066594940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266380040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442663800423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442663800.jpg  a978-3-11-066594-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles